{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_4","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc 'rg -n \"workflow|stage|session|story session|domain model|enum|WorkflowStage|SessionStage|composition|audio job|event log\" .'","aggregated_output":"./secrets.example.yaml:15:  composition_model: gemini-3.1-pro\n./secrets.example.yaml:23:    sessions: storyteller-sessions\n./README.md:3:Storyteller is a local-first, full-stack app for creating bedtime stories from first idea to finished text and finished narration audio. The product is session-based: the first meaningful screen is a past-sessions view where a user can resume work in progress, reopen a completed story, or start a new session.\n./README.md:11:- See past sessions first and continue where they left off.\n./README.md:13:- Move through a structured planning workflow before long-form writing starts.\n./README.md:14:- Watch story composition and audio generation progress in real time.\n./README.md:21:The application is being built around this ordered workflow:\n./README.md:34:Each stage must be durable, resumable, and editable. Chat messages can propose actions in the workflow, and direct UI actions must also be reflected back into the session chat log as compact summaries.\n./README.md:51:- Long-running story composition and narration generation must be durable background jobs with resumable server-side state.\n./README.md:57:The repo is intended to run locally with Docker Compose. At the current scaffold stage:\n./README.md:90:`secrets.yaml` is already gitignored and reserved for local-only credentials. `make bootstrap` will create it from `secrets.example.yaml` when needed, but you still need to replace the placeholder Gemini API key before using AI-backed workflows. The repo-managed Git hook blocks accidental commits of `secrets.yaml`, `.env` files, and obvious live key material. The compose file uses development defaults for Postgres and the GCS emulator, while the backend loads secrets from the repo-root `secrets.yaml` at container startup.\n./README.md:128:Use `make up`, `make down`, and `make logs` for the common compose workflow. The existing wrapper script remains the canonical compose entrypoint underneath those targets, so advanced commands can still go through:\n./README.md:145:- `STORYTELLER_GCS_SESSIONS_BUCKET_NAME=storyteller-sessions`\n./README.md:199:- the first screen is the past-sessions home for resume, edit, and create flows\n./README.md:200:- the story workflow is staged and ordered\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:10:Storyteller is a full-stack application with a browser client, a backend-owned workflow engine, durable relational state, durable object storage, and resumable background jobs.\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:20:        |         +--> AI adapters for planning, composition, and narration\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:22:        |         +--> repositories for sessions, workflow state, jobs, and event log\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:24:        +--> background workers for composition and audio generation\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:35:2. Policy enforcement: chat-to-UI actions and workflow transitions need deterministic server validation before the model can change session state.\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:36:3. Durable orchestration: prompts, structured outputs, retries, and model selection need to be coordinated with persistent session data and job records.\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:50:The durable model should include job records, segment records, asset metadata, and an event log that can reconstruct session progress after interruption.\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:59:- `models/`: typed domain models and persistence schemas\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:60:- `repositories/`: database access for sessions, events, jobs, and assets\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:61:- `services/`: workflow logic and policy enforcement\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:62:- `ai/`: Gemini planning, composition, and narration adapters\n./docs/architecture-overview.md:71:- Workflow stage\n./backend/README.md:3:This directory is the home for the FastAPI application, backend-owned workflow logic, and future durable job processing.\n./backend/README.md:10:  - `models/`: API response models and future domain models\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:205:.session-item p {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:211:.session-list,\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:212:.stage-list {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:247:.session-list {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:252:.session-item {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:262:.session-item h3 {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:284:.stage-list {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:290:.stage-list li {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:300:.stage-list span {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:391:  .stage-list {\n./frontend/src/styles/index.css:407:  .session-item {\n./docs/system-diagram.md:3:This diagram shows the intended runtime shape for Storyteller after the core session, worker, and realtime prompts are built. It documents where session resume, durable event history, realtime delivery, and long-running jobs belong.\n./docs/system-diagram.md:7:    Browser[\"Browser UI<br/>React + Vite<br/>sessions home, chat pane, workflow pane\"]\n./docs/system-diagram.md:8:    API[\"FastAPI API<br/>routes, policy checks, session reads/writes\"]\n./docs/system-diagram.md:9:    WS[\"WebSocket session stream<br/>replay recent events + deliver live progress\"]\n./docs/system-diagram.md:10:    Worker[\"Worker process<br/>composition jobs, audio jobs, retries, interruption\"]\n./docs/system-diagram.md:11:    Postgres[(\"PostgreSQL<br/>sessions, workflow state,<br/>durable event history,<br/>job records, asset metadata\")]\n./docs/system-diagram.md:13:    Gemini[\"Gemini adapters<br/>planning, composition, narration\"]\n./docs/system-diagram.md:16:    API -->|\"resume session snapshot\"| Browser\n./docs/system-diagram.md:28:    Worker -->|\"planning, composition, TTS calls\"| Gemini\n./docs/system-diagram.md:35:- Resume starts from PostgreSQL session state plus durable event history.\n./prompts/76-audio-preview-and-segment-status-ui.md:10:- Build the audio stage UI with a progress bar, segment status list, estimated remaining work, and any ready-for-preview audio clips if available.\n./prompts/76-audio-preview-and-segment-status-ui.md:28:Use the same design language as composition progress.\n./docs/contributing.md:23:- Prefer names that describe product concepts directly: `session`, `pitch`, `beat_sheet`, `audio_job`.\n./docs/contributing.md:28:- Put durable workflow logic in backend services or repositories, not in route modules or frontend components.\n./docs/contributing.md:30:- Treat the backend as the source of truth for workflow stage, job progress, and AI side effects. The browser reflects state; it does not own it.\n./docs/contributing.md:43:- Do not mix generated files into source directories. If a workflow needs checked-in fixtures, place stable fixtures under `test-assets/` and document why they are committed.\n./prompts/53-outline-drill-down.md:7:Transform the high-level beat sheet into a more detailed chapter or scene plan that composition can execute in segments.\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:7:staged_paths=()\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:9:  staged_paths+=(\"${path}\")\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:12:if [[ \"${#staged_paths[@]}\" -eq 0 ]]; then\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:18:for path in \"${staged_paths[@]}\"; do\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:43:staged_patch=\"$(git diff --cached --unified=0 --no-color -- .)\"\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:44:added_lines=\"$(printf '%s\\n' \"${staged_patch}\" | rg '^\\+' | rg -v '^\\+\\+\\+' || true)\"\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:52:  printf 'Detected staged private key material:\\n%s\\n' \"${private_key_hits}\" >&2\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:58:  printf 'Detected staged Gemini or Google API key material:\\n%s\\n' \"${gemini_key_hits}\" >&2\n./scripts/check-secret-hygiene.sh:69:  printf 'Detected staged secret assignment lines:\\n%s\\n' \"${assigned_secret_hits}\" >&2\n./docs/product-brief.md:5:Storyteller is a session-based bedtime story creation studio. It helps a user move from a loose story idea to a finished written story and finished narration audio, with the ability to leave and come back later without losing progress.\n./docs/product-brief.md:7:The first meaningful screen is the sessions home. It must foreground past sessions, including both in-progress and completed stories, so resume and revisit are the default behaviors rather than an afterthought.\n./docs/product-brief.md:12:- Guided, not opaque: users move through explicit workflow stages instead of one giant prompt box.\n./docs/product-brief.md:37:- A user can reopen a session from any stage.\n./docs/product-brief.md:38:- In-progress and completed sessions both appear on the home screen.\n./docs/product-brief.md:44:- Right pane is the main workflow UI, about two-thirds width.\n./docs/product-brief.md:49:- The model may propose actions, but a deterministic backend policy layer decides whether each action is valid for the session's current stage.\n./docs/product-brief.md:84:- resume work from prior sessions without losing context\n./prompts/71-audio-length-estimation.md:11:- Show the estimate in the audio stage UI and update it when the user changes speed or when the story draft changes materially.\n./backend/tests/test_settings.py:35:    monkeypatch.setenv(\"STORYTELLER_GCS_SESSIONS_BUCKET_NAME\", \"storyteller-sessions\")\n./backend/tests/test_settings.py:50:    assert settings.gcs_bucket_names.sessions == \"storyteller-sessions\"\n./backend/tests/test_settings.py:71:            sessions: storyteller-sessions\n./backend/tests/test_settings.py:114:            sessions: storyteller-sessions\n./backend/tests/test_settings.py:163:    assert settings.gcs_bucket_names.sessions == \"storyteller-dev\"\n./backend/tests/test_settings.py:179:    monkeypatch.setenv(\"STORYTELLER_GCS_SESSIONS_BUCKET_NAME\", \"storyteller-sessions\")\n./prompts/43-brief-normalization-service.md:7:Use Gemini to turn the user’s free-form brief into a structured planning summary that later stages can rely on.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.yolopilot.md:6:- Compact event log: `/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.yolopilot.jsonlines`\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.yolopilot.md:68:- Summary: I’m inspecting the current repo state and the existing session/workflow code first so the domain model and state machine line up with what’s already implemented instead of introducing a parallel design.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.yolopilot.md:72:    I’m inspecting the current repo state and the existing session/workflow code first so the domain model and state machine line up with what’s already implemented instead of introducing a parallel design.\n./backend/tests/test_health.py:23:            \"storyteller-sessions, storyteller-audio, storyteller-exports at \"\n./docs/README.md:7:- `product-brief.md`: product expectations and workflow\n./prompts/35-chat-commands-and-quick-actions.md:10:- Support a few simple slash-style commands or quick action chips such as regenerate pitches, summarize current plan, pause writing, resume writing, or move to next stage.\n./scripts/README.md:8:- `check-secret-hygiene.sh`: blocks staged local-only config files and obvious secret material\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:9:The product is a guided story-creation studio with a persistent session model. A user should be able to:\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:11:1. See past story sessions first, including both in-progress and completed work.\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:12:2. Open a session to resume, edit, or finalize it.\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:15:   - **Main pane:** structured workflow UI, about two-thirds of the desktop width.\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:18:   - The user can act directly in the UI, and those actions should be reflected in the chat log and in durable session state.\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:19:5. Move through a staged workflow:\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:49:The session should support this exact conceptual flow:\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:75:   - The user can interrupt and redirect composition, including causing rewrites of prior segments.\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:92:- Past sessions screen must be the first meaningful screen\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:108:- Use the **Gemini 3.1 family** for text/planning/composition workloads\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:141:- Workflow stage\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:159:Treat composition and audio generation as **durable background jobs**, not request-thread work.\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:190:The model can **propose** actions, but a deterministic policy layer should decide whether they are valid in the current session state.\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:197:- The composition stage should write against the beat sheet and the detailed outline derived from it.\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:247:- making stage transitions implicit or magical\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:269:- **High-value reasoning / plan synthesis / long-form composition:** Gemini 3.1 Pro class model\n./prompts/base_prompt.md:277:Build this as a durable, session-based, full-stack application — not a single-shot prompt demo.\n./infra/compose/docker-compose.yml:72:      STORYTELLER_GCS_SESSIONS_BUCKET_NAME: storyteller-sessions\n./backend/tests/conftest.py:17:    \"STORYTELLER_GCS_SESSIONS_BUCKET_NAME\": \"storyteller-sessions\",\n./prompts/50-story-length-duration-and-chapter-setup.md:7:Implement the story setup stage where the user can choose soft planning targets such as word count, estimated read-aloud duration, and chapter organization.\n./prompts/50-story-length-duration-and-chapter-setup.md:12:- Explain in the UI that these parameters are correlated suggestions that guide composition instead of rigid constraints.\n./prompts/55-continuity-bible.md:7:Create a structured continuity record that helps the app stay consistent during long composition and rewrite flows.\n./prompts/55-continuity-bible.md:11:- Update the continuity bible when the user accepts major planning decisions and when composition locks in details worth preserving.\n./prompts/55-continuity-bible.md:17:- Update hooks from planning stages\n./prompts/55-continuity-bible.md:23:- Continuity data can inform later composition prompts and rewrite decisions.\n./prompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md:7:Improve the session library so finished stories are easy to find and revisit later.\n./prompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md:10:- Enhance the home screen with searching, filtering, or grouping for sessions by status, genre, date, or title.\n./prompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md:11:- Add richer summary metadata for completed sessions such as final title, total runtime, and artifact readiness.\n./prompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md:12:- Make it easy to distinguish a draft session from a polished completed story.\n./prompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md:16:- Enhanced session library UI\n./prompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md:18:- Completed-session summary metadata\n./prompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md:22:- The library scales beyond a handful of sessions.\n./prompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md:32:`feat(prompt-86): completed session summary and search`\n./docs/secrets-and-local-config.md:65:The hook blocks commits that stage `secrets.yaml`, `.env` files, or obvious Gemini/private-key material.\n./docs/secrets-and-local-config.md:83:    sessions: storyteller-sessions\n./docs/secrets-and-local-config.md:103:- `gcs.buckets.sessions`\n./prompts/68-autosave-drafts-and-partials.md:7:Persist partial story drafts during composition so crashes or reconnects do not destroy progress.\n./prompts/68-autosave-drafts-and-partials.md:10:- Save accepted text snapshots and/or rolling draft artifacts during composition to durable storage.\n./prompts/68-autosave-drafts-and-partials.md:11:- Record enough metadata to restore the latest stable draft view on session resume.\n./prompts/68-autosave-drafts-and-partials.md:16:- Autosave logic for composition\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.test.tsx:24:    expect(screen.getByText('Past sessions come first')).toBeInTheDocument()\n./prompts/09-initial-system-diagram-and-adr.md:23:- The diagram includes session resume and durable event history as first-class concepts.\n./prompts/34-ui-events-to-agent-context.md:7:Ensure the agent can see important UI-side changes so follow-up chat turns are grounded in the current session rather than stale assumptions.\n./prompts/34-ui-events-to-agent-context.md:11:- Update the session snapshot and any rolling context summary used by the backend agent services.\n./docs/adr/README.md:9:- `0001-core-runtime-architecture.md`: backend-owned AI calls, durable Postgres session state, file-backed GCS assets, websocket live updates, separate workers for long-running jobs, and soft planning constraints\n./scripts/bootstrap-dev.sh:70:  printf 'Reminder: replace the placeholder Gemini API key in %s before using AI-backed workflows.\\n' \"${SECRETS_FILE}\"\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:9:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_3\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"rg --files -g 'README.md' -g 'docs/**' -g 'prompts/**' -g 'AGENTS.md'\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines\\nprompts/36-conversation-memory-summaries.md\\nprompts/99-release-checklist-and-future-roadmap.md\\nprompts/44-pitch-generation-pipeline.md\\nprompts/42-story-setup-brief-form.md\\nprompts/07-developer-bootstrap-scripts.md\\nprompts/20-frontend-app-shell-and-routing.md\\nprompts/52-bedtime-safety-and-content-guidelines.md\\nprompts/02-vite-react-scaffold.md\\nprompts/78-download-endpoints-and-object-access.md\\nprompts/01-monorepo-skeleton.md\\nprompts/13-storage-abstraction-and-buckets.md\\nprompts/48-save-the-cat-beat-sheet-generation.md\\nprompts/95-ci-pipeline.md\\nprompts/46-character-sheet-generation.md\\nprompts/83-artifact-packaging-and-links.md\\nprompts/11-postgres-schema-and-migrations.md\\nprompts/06-gitignore-and-secrets-hygiene.md\\nprompts/65-interrupt-and-redirect-composition.md\\nprompts/30-chat-to-ui-action-schema.md\\nprompts/37-agent-tool-registry.md\\nprompts/54-chapter-scene-card-editor.md\\nprompts/62-composition-streaming-events.md\\nprompts/26-main-pane-stage-scaffold.md\\nprompts/56-revision-history-and-branches.md\\nprompts/00-project-charter.md\\nprompts/88-artifact-retention-and-cleanup.md\\nprompts/63-composition-main-pane-ui.md\\nprompts/74-background-music-mixing.md\\nprompts/14-repositories-and-session-service.md\\nprompts/61-segmented-writing-engine.md\\nprompts/67-diff-and-compare-ui.md\\nprompts/17-realtime-event-schema.md\\nprompts/90-local-identity-and-future-auth-shape.md\\nprompts/80-finalize-screen-read-and-listen.md\\nprompts/45-pitch-refinement-via-chat.md\\nprompts/92-observability-and-logging.md\\nprompts/72-narration-segmentation.md\\nprompts/04-docker-compose-foundation.md\\nprompts/64-agent-summary-messages-during-composition.md\\nprompts/41-tone-selection-api-and-ui.md\\nprompts/23-frontend-state-foundation.md\\nprompts/97-security-review.md\\nprompts/12-seed-genres-and-tones.md\\nprompts/81-docx-export-pipeline.md\\nprompts/87-developer-debug-inspector.md\\nprompts/25-chat-window-foundation.md\\nprompts/60-composition-job-orchestration.md\\nprompts/96-compose-dev-and-prod-shapes.md\\nprompts/49-beat-sheet-refinement-ui-and-chat.md\\nprompts/93-accessibility-pass-and-keyboard-support.md\\nprompts/15-event-log-and-audit-trail.md\\nprompts/47-character-refinement-via-chat.md\\nprompts/16-asset-metadata-and-file-records.md\\nprompts/76-audio-preview-and-segment-status-ui.md\\nprompts/53-outline-drill-down.md\\nprompts/66-rewrite-prior-segments.md\\nprompts/18-postgres-job-runner-skeleton.md\\nprompts/43-brief-normalization-service.md\\nprompts/base_prompt.md\\nprompts/50-story-length-duration-and-chapter-setup.md\\nprompts/86-completed-session-summary-and-search.md\\nprompts/82-html-markdown-and-reader-formatting.md\\nprompts/77-final-audio-assembly.md\\nprompts/79-audio-pipeline-tests.md\\nprompts/34-ui-events-to-agent-context.md\\nprompts/89-full-journey-e2e-test.md\\nprompts/57-composition-prompt-assembly.md\\nprompts/39-bridge-and-replay-tests.md\\nprompts/03-fastapi-scaffold.md\\nprompts/31-intent-parser-service.md\\nprompts/75-audio-job-orchestration.md\\nprompts/00-project-charter.yolopilot.md\\nprompts/85-audio-player-with-text-sync-hooks.md\\nprompts/05-backend-settings-and-secrets-loading.md\\nprompts/33-action-echoes-in-chat.md\\nprompts/08-repo-quality-tooling.md\\nprompts/19-data-layer-integration-tests.md\\nprompts/73-gemini-tts-integration.md\\nprompts/71-audio-length-estimation.md\\nprompts/22-workspace-two-pane-layout.md\\nprompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md\\nprompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md\\nprompts/40-genre-selection-api-and-ui.md\\nprompts/70-audio-settings-model-and-ui.md\\nprompts/69-composition-loop-e2e-test.md\\nprompts/00-project-charter.yolopilot.jsonlines\\nprompts/27-reusable-form-and-card-components.md\\nprompts/98-demo-data-and-onboarding.md\\nprompts/21-past-sessions-home-screen.md\\nprompts/51-correlation-heuristics.md\\nprompts/35-chat-commands-and-quick-actions.md\\nprompts/55-continuity-bible.md\\nprompts/28-error-loading-and-feedback-states.md\\nprompts/32-ui-action-policy-engine.md\\nprompts/94-performance-pass.md\\nprompts/29-frontend-websocket-client-skeleton.md\\nprompts/58-usage-cost-and-latency-metrics.md\\nprompts/68-autosave-drafts-and-partials.md\\nprompts/09-initial-system-diagram-and-adr.md\\nprompts/91-rate-limits-retries-and-fallbacks.md\\nprompts/24-design-tokens-and-accessibility-foundation.md\\nprompts/84-reader-ui-with-navigation.md\\nprompts/59-planning-funnel-e2e-test.md\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:13:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_6\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,220p' prompts/00-project-charter.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# 00 — Project Charter and Success Criteria\\n\\nRead `base_prompt.md` first and preserve all prior prompt work.\\n\\n## Objective\\n\\nCreate the initial project framing for a full-stack app that helps a user build a bedtime story, turn it into audio, and resume past sessions.\\n\\n## Build\\n- Write a top-level README that explains the product vision, the end-to-end story workflow, the required stages, and the major technical choices already fixed by the brief.\\n- Document the non-negotiable requirements: React + Vite frontend, Python FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL for all structured data, a file-backed GCS emulator for blobs, Docker Compose for local orchestration, and `secrets.yaml` kept out of git.\\n- Add a short architecture note describing why all Gemini calls must happen on the backend and why long-running composition and audio jobs need resumable server-side state.\\n\\n## Deliverables\\n\\n- `README.md` with product overview and local development expectations\\n- `docs/product-brief.md` or equivalent design note\\n- `docs/architecture-overview.md` with the first cut of the system picture\\n\\n## Acceptance checks\\n\\n- A new engineer can read the repo root and understand what is being built.\\n- The required story stages from the brief are explicitly listed in order.\\n- The first screen requirement — a past-sessions screen for resume/edit/create — is called out early, not buried.\\n\\n## Notes\\n\\nDo not generate implementation code yet beyond lightweight documentation scaffolding.\\n\\n## Suggested commit label\\n\\n`feat(prompt-00): project charter`\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:14:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_5\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' prompts/base_prompt.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Base Prompt — Build the Bedtime Story + Audio App\\n\\nYou are building a production-minded local-first application that helps a user create a bedtime story from idea to finished text and finished narration audio.\\n\\nThis prompt pack is designed to be used **sequentially**. Read this file first, then work through the numbered prompts in order. Each numbered prompt should be treated as an incremental implementation task inside the same repository. Preserve prior work unless the new prompt explicitly asks you to refactor it.\\n\\n## Product Summary\\n\\nThe product is a guided story-creation studio with a persistent session model. A user should be able to:\\n\\n1. See past story sessions first, including both in-progress and completed work.\\n2. Open a session to resume, edit, or finalize it.\\n3. Use a **two-pane workspace**:\\n   - **Left pane:** chat window, about one-third of the desktop width.\\n   - **Main pane:** structured workflow UI, about two-thirds of the desktop width.\\n4. Control the product in **both directions**:\\n   - The user can type in chat, and the system can translate those messages into UI actions.\\n   - The user can act directly in the UI, and those actions should be reflected in the chat log and in durable session state.\\n5. Move through a staged workflow:\\n   - Genre selection\\n   - Tone selection\\n   - Story setup / free-form brief\\n   - Story pitches\\n   - Character sheet\\n   - Save-the-Cat beat sheet\\n   - Story setup preferences such as word count, runtime, and chapters\\n   - Composition\\n   - Audio configuration and audio generation\\n   - Finalize / read / listen / download\\n6. Download the final story as a **Word document** and the final narration as an audio file.\\n7. Read or listen inside the product UI after generation is complete.\\n\\n## Story-Generation Philosophy\\n\\nThe app is for **bedtime stories**, not generic fiction generation. That means:\\n\\n- Wonder is welcome.\\n- Adventure is welcome.\\n- Mystery is welcome.\\n- Tension is allowed, but it should be modulated for bedtime use.\\n- Emotional repair matters.\\n- The ending should feel safe, satisfying, and restful.\\n- The narration and UI tone should remain calm, readable, and trustworthy.\\n\\nUse the research docs in this prompt pack as direct product input, especially the Save The Cat notes and the curated genre/tone catalog.\\n\\n## Required Story Workflow\\n\\nThe session should support this exact conceptual flow:\\n\\n1. **Genre Selection**\\n   - The user selects from the curated genre list.\\n2. **Tone Selection**\\n   - The user is shown preconfigured tone options for the chosen genre.\\n3. **Story Setup**\\n   - The user provides a free-form description of the story they want to tell.\\n4. **Story Pitches**\\n   - Gemini generates multiple candidate pitches.\\n   - The user can select one, ask for alternatives, or refine via chat.\\n5. **Character Sheet**\\n   - Gemini generates multiple candidate character sheets.\\n   - The user can select or refine via chat.\\n6. **Story Beats**\\n   - Gemini generates a Save-the-Cat beat sheet for the selected plan.\\n   - The user can refine the beats via chat or UI.\\n7. **Story Setup Preferences**\\n   - The user can set soft planning targets such as word count, read-aloud duration, and chapter organization.\\n   - These are **guides**, not strict constraints.\\n8. **Composition**\\n   - The system writes in segments.\\n   - The UI shows a live typewriter-like experience.\\n   - Writing should generally appear faster than the user can comfortably read.\\n   - A visible progress bar should show overall story progress.\\n   - The agent should periodically post chat summaries of what it is writing.\\n   - The user can interrupt and redirect composition, including causing rewrites of prior segments.\\n9. **Audio**\\n   - The user configures voice, music, speed, and related settings.\\n   - The system estimates final length heuristically.\\n   - Audio is generated in segments with visible progress.\\n10. **Finalize**\\n   - The user can read and listen in the UI.\\n   - The user can download the story as a Word document and the final audio as a file.\\n\\n## Non-Negotiable Technical Requirements\\n\\n### Frontend\\n- React\\n- Vite\\n- TypeScript\\n- The browser must **never** hold provider secrets\\n- Chat pane on the left, main pane on the right\\n- Past sessions screen must be the first meaningful screen\\n\\n### Backend\\n- Python\\n- FastAPI\\n- Durable backend-owned business logic\\n- Clear separation between route handlers, domain services, AI orchestration, and persistence\\n\\n### Data and Infrastructure\\n- PostgreSQL is the durable store for structured application state\\n- Use a **file-backed GCS emulator** for object/blob storage in local development\\n- The app must run with Docker Compose\\n- Postgres and object storage must both be **persistent across restarts**\\n- `secrets.yaml` exists locally for API keys and must **not** be committed to git\\n\\n### AI\\n- Use the **Gemini 3.1 family** for text/planning/composition workloads\\n- Keep model IDs centralized in config, not scattered through the codebase\\n- Put AI calls behind backend services and adapters\\n- Use structured outputs wherever determinism matters\\n- Use separate adapters for:\\n  - planning/classification/intent parsing\\n  - long-form story generation\\n  - narration / TTS\\n- Keep narration generation isolated behind a provider-style interface because model offerings evolve\\n\\n## Recommended Architecture\\n\\nUse a calm, maintainable architecture rather than a clever one.\\n\\n### Suggested application shape\\n- `frontend/` — React + Vite app\\n- `backend/` — FastAPI app plus domain services\\n- `infra/` — Docker Compose, Dockerfiles, local infrastructure helpers\\n- `docs/` — architecture notes, ADRs, product docs\\n\\n### Suggested backend layers\\n- `api/` or route handlers\\n- `settings/`\\n- `db/`\\n- `models/`\\n- `repositories/`\\n- `services/`\\n- `worker/`\\n- `ai/`\\n- `storage/`\\n\\n### Suggested durable concepts\\n- Session\\n- Workflow stage\\n- Event log\\n- Selected genre\\n- Selected tone\\n- Story brief\\n- Pitch batch + selected pitch\\n- Character batch + selected character sheet\\n- Beat sheet\\n- Story setup preferences\\n- Outline / chapter or scene plan\\n- Continuity bible\\n- Composition job\\n- Composition segment\\n- Audio job\\n- Asset record\\n\\n## Real-Time and Long-Running Work\\n\\nTreat composition and audio generation as **durable background jobs**, not request-thread work.\\n\\n- The browser should be able to refresh without losing the job.\\n- The UI should receive live progress updates.\\n- The backend should own current truth about progress.\\n- A separate worker process is strongly preferred.\\n- Use PostgreSQL-backed durable job records.\\n- Persist partial outputs frequently enough that resume is trustworthy.\\n\\n## Chat and UI Bridge Rules\\n\\nThe product must support true bidirectional interaction.\\n\\n### Chat-to-UI\\nA user message can propose actions like:\\n- select a tone\\n- regenerate pitches\\n- choose a pitch\\n- adjust character traits\\n- soften the midpoint\\n- shorten the story target\\n- pause writing\\n- change narration speed\\n\\n### UI-to-Chat\\nA direct UI action should appear in the chat history as a compact structured summary, for example:\\n- “Selected genre: Quest Fantasy”\\n- “Updated target runtime: ~12 minutes”\\n- “Accepted revised beat sheet”\\n\\n### Safety rule\\nThe model can **propose** actions, but a deterministic policy layer should decide whether they are valid in the current session state.\\n\\n## Save The Cat Expectations\\n\\nUse the Save The Cat method as the backbone of planning.\\n\\n- The beat sheet should be explicit, editable, and stored as structured data.\\n- The composition stage should write against the beat sheet and the detailed outline derived from it.\\n- Bedtime adaptation matters: the low points can be emotionally meaningful without becoming harsh or distressing.\\n- The final story should still feel like a transformation story, not just a string of nice scenes.\\n\\n## Genre and Tone Expectations\\n\\nUse the included research docs to seed:\\n- a curated genre list\\n- per-genre tone options\\n- bedtime-suitable arc notes\\n- tone descriptors that can guide UI copy and AI prompting\\n\\nDo **not** label tones with living or copyrighted-author names. Use generic tone labels and descriptors.\\n\\n## Audio Expectations\\n\\nNarration must be treated as a real product feature, not a side demo.\\n\\n- Segment audio generation so it is resumable\\n- Estimate length heuristically before generation\\n- Support voice selection\\n- Support speed controls\\n- Support optional background music\\n- Keep music subordinate to narration clarity\\n- Produce a final compiled audio artifact\\n- Keep intermediate and final artifacts trackable through durable metadata\\n\\n## Export Expectations\\n\\nAt minimum, the user must be able to get:\\n- final story text in the app\\n- final audio in the app\\n- downloadable `.docx`\\n- downloadable final audio file\\n\\n## Developer Experience and Quality Bar\\n\\nFavor:\\n- typed interfaces\\n- boring, explicit service boundaries\\n- migrations\\n- tests around durable state\\n- visible logs\\n- simple scripts for local dev\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:30:{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_15\",\"type\":\"todo_list\",\"items\":[{\"text\":\"Draft top-level README with product vision, ordered workflow, fixed technology decisions, and local development expectations\",\"completed\":false},{\"text\":\"Add docs/product-brief.md and docs/architecture-overview.md aligned to the prompt and current scaffold\",\"completed\":false},{\"text\":\"Verify content against acceptance criteria, commit a checkpoint, and write prompts/00-project-charter.summary.md as the final action\",\"completed\":false}]}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:34:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_18\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"The draft docs are in place. I’m running structured checks now against the exact acceptance criteria: required files, the past-sessions-first requirement, the ordered workflow, and the fixed stack decisions.\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:38:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_20\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' docs/product-brief.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Product Brief\\n\\n## Product Summary\\n\\nStoryteller is a session-based bedtime story creation studio. It helps a user move from a loose story idea to a finished written story and finished narration audio, with the ability to leave and come back later without losing progress.\\n\\nThe first meaningful screen is the sessions home. It must foreground past sessions, including both in-progress and completed stories, so resume and revisit are the default behaviors rather than an afterthought.\\n\\n## User Experience Principles\\n\\n- Bedtime-first: stories should support calm endings, emotional repair, and low-friction read-aloud use.\\n- Guided, not opaque: users move through explicit workflow stages instead of one giant prompt box.\\n- Bidirectional control: chat can suggest UI actions, and UI actions must be echoed back into chat.\\n- Durable by default: progress survives refreshes, restarts, and long-running generation work.\\n- Local-first development: the full stack should run locally through Docker Compose with persistent infrastructure.\\n\\n## End-to-End Workflow\\n\\nThe product must support this ordered flow:\\n\\n1. Genre selection from a curated genre list.\\n2. Tone selection from options preconfigured for the chosen genre.\\n3. Story setup through a free-form brief describing the desired story.\\n4. Story pitches generated by Gemini, with selection, refinement, or regeneration.\\n5. Character sheet generation, again with selection and refinement.\\n6. Save-the-Cat beat sheet generation and editing.\\n7. Story setup preferences for soft targets such as word count, runtime, and chapters.\\n8. Composition in segments with visible progress, typewriter-like output, and interruptibility.\\n9. Audio configuration and audio generation, including voice and speed controls plus optional background music.\\n10. Finalize, where the user can read, listen, and download story and audio artifacts.\\n\\n## Core Product Behaviors\\n\\n### Sessions and Resume\\n\\n- Sessions are durable backend entities.\\n- A user can reopen a session from any stage.\\n- In-progress and completed sessions both appear on the home screen.\\n\\n### Workspace Layout\\n\\n- Desktop layout uses two panes.\\n- Left pane is the chat workspace, about one-third width.\\n- Right pane is the main workflow UI, about two-thirds width.\\n\\n### Chat and UI Bridge\\n\\n- User chat can propose structured actions such as selecting a tone or refining beats.\\n- The model may propose actions, but a deterministic backend policy layer decides whether each action is valid for the session's current stage.\\n- Direct UI actions must create compact chat-visible summaries for auditability and replay.\\n\\n### Composition Experience\\n\\n- Story writing happens in segments.\\n- Progress is visible and should feel meaningfully live.\\n- The system should periodically summarize what it is writing in chat.\\n- Users can interrupt, redirect, and request rewrites.\\n\\n### Audio Experience\\n\\n- Narration is a first-class feature, not a demo extra.\\n- Audio generation is segmented and resumable.\\n- The app estimates likely runtime before generation starts.\\n- Final audio should be playable in-app and downloadable.\\n\\n## Non-Negotiable Technical Constraints\\n\\n- Frontend: React, Vite, TypeScript\\n- Backend: Python, FastAPI\\n- Structured persistence: PostgreSQL\\n- Object storage in local development: file-backed GCS emulator\\n- Local orchestration: Docker Compose\\n- Secrets: local `secrets.yaml`, excluded from git\\n- AI model family: Gemini 3.1, with backend-owned adapters and centralized model configuration\\n\\n## Deliverable Expectations\\n\\nThe finished product should let a user:\\n\\n- create and revise a bedtime story plan\\n- generate and edit a complete story\\n- generate, play, and download narration audio\\n- download the story as `.docx`\\n- resume work from prior sessions without losing context\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:39:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_19\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,260p' docs/architecture-overview.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Architecture Overview\\n\\n## System Picture\\n\\nStoryteller is a full-stack application with a browser client, a backend-owned workflow engine, durable relational state, durable object storage, and resumable background jobs.\\n\\n```text\\nReact + Vite client\\n        |\\n        v\\nFastAPI API layer\\n        |\\n        +--> domain services and policy layer\\n        |         |\\n        |         +--> AI adapters for planning, composition, and narration\\n        |         |\\n        |         +--> repositories for sessions, workflow state, jobs, and event log\\n        |\\n        +--> background workers for composition and audio generation\\n                  |\\n                  +--> PostgreSQL for durable structured state\\n                  +--> file-backed GCS emulator for artifacts and intermediate blobs\\n```\\n\\n## Why Gemini Calls Must Stay on the Backend\\n\\nAll Gemini access belongs on the server side for four reasons:\\n\\n1. Secrets control: provider credentials live in local `secrets.yaml` and must never enter the browser.\\n2. Policy enforcement: chat-to-UI actions and workflow transitions need deterministic server validation before the model can change session state.\\n3. Durable orchestration: prompts, structured outputs, retries, and model selection need to be coordinated with persistent session data and job records.\\n4. Provider flexibility: keeping Gemini behind backend adapters lets the app keep a stable internal interface while model IDs, structured output tactics, or narration providers evolve.\\n\\nThe frontend should only call the backend's API and subscribe to backend-owned progress events.\\n\\n## Why Composition and Audio Must Use Resumable Server-Side Jobs\\n\\nComposition and narration are long-running operations that cannot safely live inside request threads or browser memory. They need server-side jobs because:\\n\\n- a user must be able to refresh the page or return later without losing progress\\n- partial story text and audio segments need durable checkpoints\\n- progress updates need a single source of truth that both chat and UI can observe\\n- retries, cancellation, and resume logic need explicit job state rather than transient in-memory state\\n\\nThe durable model should include job records, segment records, asset metadata, and an event log that can reconstruct session progress after interruption.\\n\\n## Intended Backend Shape\\n\\nThe target backend should separate concerns explicitly:\\n\\n- `api/`: HTTP routes and websocket endpoints\\n- `settings/`: environment and secrets loading\\n- `db/`: database engine, migrations, and persistence setup\\n- `models/`: typed domain models and persistence schemas\\n- `repositories/`: database access for sessions, events, jobs, and assets\\n- `services/`: workflow logic and policy enforcement\\n- `ai/`: Gemini planning, composition, and narration adapters\\n- `worker/`: background job execution for writing and audio\\n- `storage/`: object storage abstraction over the local GCS emulator\\n\\n## Durable Domain Concepts\\n\\nThe system should persist the following concepts as first-class records:\\n\\n- Session\\n- Workflow stage\\n- Event log\\n- Selected genre\\n- Selected tone\\n- Story brief\\n- Pitch batch and selected pitch\\n- Character batch and selected character sheet\\n- Beat sheet\\n- Story setup preferences\\n- Outline or chapter plan\\n- Continuity bible\\n- Composition job and segments\\n- Audio job and segments\\n- Asset metadata\\n\\n## Current Repository State\\n\\nThe repository currently contains an initial scaffold:\\n\\n- `frontend/`: Vite React app\\n- `backend/`: FastAPI app\\n- `docker-compose.yml`: local frontend, backend, and browser QA services\\n- `tools/webapp-qa/`: containerized browser automation support\\n\\nPostgreSQL, the file-backed GCS emulator, background workers, and most domain layers are still planned work. This document records the required direction so later prompts can extend the scaffold without changing the architectural contract.\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:40:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_21\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' README.md\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"# Storyteller\\n\\nStoryteller is a local-first, full-stack app for creating bedtime stories from first idea to finished text and finished narration audio. The product is session-based: the first meaningful screen is a past-sessions view where a user can resume work in progress, reopen a completed story, or start a new session.\\n\\nThis repository currently contains the first scaffold for that system. The project charter in this README and the supporting docs define the product and architecture that later prompts will implement.\\n\\n## Product Vision\\n\\nThe app should feel like a guided bedtime story studio, not a generic prompt box. A user should be able to:\\n\\n- See past sessions first and continue where they left off.\\n- Collaborate through both chat and direct UI controls.\\n- Move through a structured planning workflow before long-form writing starts.\\n- Watch story composition and audio generation progress in real time.\\n- Return later to read, listen, download, or revise completed work.\\n\\nThe tone of the product should stay calm, readable, and trustworthy. Wonder, mystery, and adventure are welcome, but bedtime suitability is a hard requirement: emotional stakes should resolve safely and the ending should feel restful.\\n\\n## Required Story Workflow\\n\\nThe application is being built around this ordered workflow:\\n\\n1. Genre selection\\n2. Tone selection\\n3. Story setup / free-form brief\\n4. Story pitches\\n5. Character sheet\\n6. Save-the-Cat beat sheet\\n7. Story setup preferences such as word count, runtime, and chapters\\n8. Composition\\n9. Audio configuration and audio generation\\n10. Finalize / read / listen / download\\n\\nEach stage must be durable, resumable, and editable. Chat messages can propose actions in the workflow, and direct UI actions must also be reflected back into the session chat log as compact summaries.\\n\\n## Fixed Technical Decisions\\n\\nThese choices are not optional for this project:\\n\\n- Frontend: React + Vite + TypeScript\\n- Backend: Python + FastAPI\\n- Structured data: PostgreSQL\\n- Blob storage: file-backed GCS emulator in local development\\n- Local orchestration: Docker Compose\\n- Secrets handling: local `secrets.yaml`, never committed to git\\n- AI access: Gemini 3.1 family behind backend-owned adapters and services\\n\\nTwo architectural rules follow from those constraints:\\n\\n- The browser must never hold provider secrets or call Gemini directly.\\n- Long-running story composition and narration generation must be durable background jobs with resumable server-side state.\\n\\nMore detail is in [docs/product-brief.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/product-brief.md) and [docs/architecture-overview.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/architecture-overview.md).\\n\\n## Local Development Expectations\\n\\nThe repo is intended to run locally with Docker Compose. At the current scaffold stage:\\n\\n- `frontend/` contains a Vite React app served on `http://localhost:8566`\\n- `backend/` contains a FastAPI app served on `http://localhost:8565`\\n- `tools/webapp-qa/` contains the browser automation container used for local UI verification\\n\\nStart the current stack with:\\n\\n```bash\\ndocker compose up --build\\n```\\n\\nThe current scaffold does not yet include PostgreSQL or the file-backed GCS emulator, but both are required parts of the target system and will be added through later prompt work. `secrets.yaml` is already gitignored and reserved for local-only credentials.\\n\\n## Repository Shape\\n\\n- `frontend/`: React + Vite client application\\n- `backend/`: FastAPI application and future domain services\\n- `docs/`: product and architecture notes\\n- `prompts/`: sequential build prompts and task summaries\\n- `tools/`: local QA and developer tooling\\n\\n## What Success Looks Like\\n\\nA new engineer should be able to open this repository and quickly understand:\\n\\n- the first screen is the past-sessions home for resume, edit, and create flows\\n- the story workflow is staged and ordered\\n- the final product writes stories and generates narration audio durably\\n- the backend owns AI access, long-running jobs, and persistent state\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:41:{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_22\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"python - <<'PY'\\nfrom pathlib import Path\\nfiles = {\\n    'README.md': Path('README.md').read_text(),\\n    'docs/product-brief.md': Path('docs/product-brief.md').read_text(),\\n    'docs/architecture-overview.md': Path('docs/architecture-overview.md').read_text(),\\n}\\nrequired_stages = [\\n    'Genre selection',\\n    'Tone selection',\\n    'Story setup',\\n    'Story pitches',\\n    'Character sheet',\\n    'Save-the-Cat beat sheet',\\n    'Story setup preferences',\\n    'Composition',\\n    'Audio configuration and audio generation',\\n    'Finalize / read / listen / download',\\n]\\nprint('files_present:', all(Path(p).exists() for p in files))\\nprint('readme_mentions_past_sessions_early:', 'first meaningful screen is a past-sessions view' in files['README.md'])\\nfor stage in required_stages:\\n    print(stage, stage in files['README.md'])\\nchecks = {\\n    'react_vite_typescript': all(term in files['README.md'] for term in ['React + Vite + TypeScript']),\\n    'fastapi_backend': 'Python + FastAPI' in files['README.md'],\\n    'postgres': 'PostgreSQL' in files['README.md'],\\n    'gcs_emulator': 'file-backed GCS emulator' in files['README.md'],\\n    'docker_compose': 'Docker Compose' in files['README.md'],\\n    'secrets_yaml': 'secrets.yaml' in files['README.md'],\\n    'backend_gemini_note': 'Gemini' in files['docs/architecture-overview.md'] and 'backend' in files['docs/architecture-overview.md'],\\n    'resumable_jobs_note': 'resumable server-side jobs' in files['docs/architecture-overview.md'],\\n}\\nfor name, ok in checks.items():\\n    print(name, ok)\\nPY\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:42:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_22\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"python - <<'PY'\\nfrom pathlib import Path\\nfiles = {\\n    'README.md': Path('README.md').read_text(),\\n    'docs/product-brief.md': Path('docs/product-brief.md').read_text(),\\n    'docs/architecture-overview.md': Path('docs/architecture-overview.md').read_text(),\\n}\\nrequired_stages = [\\n    'Genre selection',\\n    'Tone selection',\\n    'Story setup',\\n    'Story pitches',\\n    'Character sheet',\\n    'Save-the-Cat beat sheet',\\n    'Story setup preferences',\\n    'Composition',\\n    'Audio configuration and audio generation',\\n    'Finalize / read / listen / download',\\n]\\nprint('files_present:', all(Path(p).exists() for p in files))\\nprint('readme_mentions_past_sessions_early:', 'first meaningful screen is a past-sessions view' in files['README.md'])\\nfor stage in required_stages:\\n    print(stage, stage in files['README.md'])\\nchecks = {\\n    'react_vite_typescript': all(term in files['README.md'] for term in ['React + Vite + TypeScript']),\\n    'fastapi_backend': 'Python + FastAPI' in files['README.md'],\\n    'postgres': 'PostgreSQL' in files['README.md'],\\n    'gcs_emulator': 'file-backed GCS emulator' in files['README.md'],\\n    'docker_compose': 'Docker Compose' in files['README.md'],\\n    'secrets_yaml': 'secrets.yaml' in files['README.md'],\\n    'backend_gemini_note': 'Gemini' in files['docs/architecture-overview.md'] and 'backend' in files['docs/architecture-overview.md'],\\n    'resumable_jobs_note': 'resumable server-side jobs' in files['docs/architecture-overview.md'],\\n}\\nfor name, ok in checks.items():\\n    print(name, ok)\\nPY\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"files_present: True\\nreadme_mentions_past_sessions_early: True\\nGenre selection True\\nTone selection True\\nStory setup True\\nStory pitches True\\nCharacter sheet True\\nSave-the-Cat beat sheet True\\nStory setup preferences True\\nComposition True\\nAudio configuration and audio generation True\\nFinalize / read / listen / download True\\nreact_vite_typescript True\\nfastapi_backend True\\npostgres True\\ngcs_emulator True\\ndocker_compose True\\nsecrets_yaml True\\nbackend_gemini_note True\\nresumable_jobs_note False\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:48:{\"type\":\"item.started\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_26\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"python - <<'PY'\\nfrom pathlib import Path\\nreadme = Path('README.md').read_text().casefold()\\nbrief = Path('docs/product-brief.md').read_text().casefold()\\narch = Path('docs/architecture-overview.md').read_text().casefold()\\nchecks = {\\n    'files_present': all(Path(p).exists() for p in ['README.md','docs/product-brief.md','docs/architecture-overview.md']),\\n    'past_sessions_called_out_early': 'first meaningful screen is a past-sessions view' in readme,\\n    'workflow_listed_in_order': all(s in readme for s in [\\n        '1. genre selection',\\n        '2. tone selection',\\n        '3. story setup / free-form brief',\\n        '4. story pitches',\\n        '5. character sheet',\\n        '6. save-the-cat beat sheet',\\n        '7. story setup preferences such as word count, runtime, and chapters',\\n        '8. composition',\\n        '9. audio configuration and audio generation',\\n        '10. finalize / read / listen / download',\\n    ]),\\n    'fixed_stack_documented': all(s in readme for s in [\\n        'react + vite + typescript',\\n        'python + fastapi',\\n        'postgresql',\\n        'file-backed gcs emulator',\\n        'docker compose',\\n        'secrets.yaml',\\n    ]),\\n    'backend_gemini_rationale_documented': 'why gemini calls must stay on the backend' in arch,\\n    'resumable_jobs_rationale_documented': 'why composition and audio must use resumable server-side jobs' in arch,\\n    'product_brief_has_sessions_home': 'the first meaningful screen is the sessions home' in brief,\\n}\\nfor name, ok in checks.items():\\n    print(f'{name}: {ok}')\\nPY\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"\",\"exit_code\":null,\"status\":\"in_progress\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:49:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_26\",\"type\":\"command_execution\",\"command\":\"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"python - <<'PY'\\nfrom pathlib import Path\\nreadme = Path('README.md').read_text().casefold()\\nbrief = Path('docs/product-brief.md').read_text().casefold()\\narch = Path('docs/architecture-overview.md').read_text().casefold()\\nchecks = {\\n    'files_present': all(Path(p).exists() for p in ['README.md','docs/product-brief.md','docs/architecture-overview.md']),\\n    'past_sessions_called_out_early': 'first meaningful screen is a past-sessions view' in readme,\\n    'workflow_listed_in_order': all(s in readme for s in [\\n        '1. genre selection',\\n        '2. tone selection',\\n        '3. story setup / free-form brief',\\n        '4. story pitches',\\n        '5. character sheet',\\n        '6. save-the-cat beat sheet',\\n        '7. story setup preferences such as word count, runtime, and chapters',\\n        '8. composition',\\n        '9. audio configuration and audio generation',\\n        '10. finalize / read / listen / download',\\n    ]),\\n    'fixed_stack_documented': all(s in readme for s in [\\n        'react + vite + typescript',\\n        'python + fastapi',\\n        'postgresql',\\n        'file-backed gcs emulator',\\n        'docker compose',\\n        'secrets.yaml',\\n    ]),\\n    'backend_gemini_rationale_documented': 'why gemini calls must stay on the backend' in arch,\\n    'resumable_jobs_rationale_documented': 'why composition and audio must use resumable server-side jobs' in arch,\\n    'product_brief_has_sessions_home': 'the first meaningful screen is the sessions home' in brief,\\n}\\nfor name, ok in checks.items():\\n    print(f'{name}: {ok}')\\nPY\\\"\",\"aggregated_output\":\"files_present: True\\npast_sessions_called_out_early: True\\nworkflow_listed_in_order: True\\nfixed_stack_documented: True\\nbackend_gemini_rationale_documented: True\\nresumable_jobs_rationale_documented: True\\nproduct_brief_has_sessions_home: True\\n\",\"exit_code\":0,\"status\":\"completed\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:50:{\"type\":\"item.updated\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_15\",\"type\":\"todo_list\",\"items\":[{\"text\":\"Draft top-level README with product vision, ordered workflow, fixed technology decisions, and local development expectations\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Add docs/product-brief.md and docs/architecture-overview.md aligned to the prompt and current scaffold\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Verify content against acceptance criteria, commit a checkpoint, and write prompts/00-project-charter.summary.md as the final action\",\"completed\":false}]}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:59:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_32\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"Added the project charter docs at [README.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/README.md), [docs/product-brief.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/product-brief.md), and [docs/architecture-overview.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/docs/architecture-overview.md). The README now calls out the past-sessions-first home screen early, lists the full staged workflow in order, and documents the fixed stack and local development expectations. The architecture note records the backend-only Gemini boundary and the requirement for resumable server-side composition/audio jobs.\\n\\nVerification was docs-focused: I manually reviewed all three files, ran a Python acceptance check covering file presence, first-screen wording, ordered workflow, fixed stack documentation, backend Gemini rationale, resumable jobs rationale, and sessions-home coverage in the product brief, and ran `git diff --check`, which passed. No tests, builds, browser checks, or screenshots were applicable because this task was documentation-only.\\n\\nI created the requested checkpoint commit `feat(prompt-00): project charter`, and the required reviewer summary file was written last at [prompts/00-project-charter.summary.md](/Users/kevin/code/storyteller/prompts/00-project-charter.summary.md).\"}}\n./prompts/00-project-charter.codex.jsonlines:60:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_15\",\"type\":\"todo_list\",\"items\":[{\"text\":\"Draft top-level README with product vision, ordered workflow, fixed technology decisions, and local development expectations\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Add docs/product-brief.md and docs/architecture-overview.md aligned to the prompt and current scaffold\",\"completed\":true},{\"text\":\"Verify content against acceptance criteria, commit a checkpoint, and write prompts/00-project-charter.summary.md as the final action\",\"completed\":false}]}}\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:3:const sessionPreview = [\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:21:const workflowStages = [\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:56:          keeping the product pointed at its sessions-first, workflow-driven\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:71:          <h2>Past sessions come first</h2>\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:73:            The real session list arrives in a later prompt. For now, the home\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:78:        <ul className=\"session-list\">\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:79:          {sessionPreview.map((session) => (\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:80:            <li key={session.title} className=\"session-item\">\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:82:                <h3>{session.title}</h3>\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:83:                <p>{session.note}</p>\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:85:              <span className=\"status-chip\">{session.status}</span>\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:96:            the staged workflow the product needs.\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:100:        <ol className=\"stage-list\">\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:101:          {workflowStages.map((stage, index) => (\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:102:            <li key={stage}>\n./frontend/src/features/home/HomeRoute.tsx:104:              <strong>{stage}</strong>\n./prompts/91-rate-limits-retries-and-fallbacks.md:7:Harden the app against transient Gemini failures, quota issues, and worker retries so long workflows do not fail messily.\n./prompts/91-rate-limits-retries-and-fallbacks.md:10:- Add retry and backoff behavior where it is safe for planning, composition, and audio generation calls.\n./prompts/91-rate-limits-retries-and-fallbacks.md:22:- Transient provider issues do not instantly poison the whole session.\n./prompts/89-full-journey-e2e-test.md:7:Add a comprehensive test that walks through the entire product from starting a session to downloading finished artifacts.\n./prompts/89-full-journey-e2e-test.md:10:- Cover the full user journey: create session, pick genre/tone, enter brief, choose/refine pitch, choose/refine character sheet, review beat sheet, set story length, compose, configure audio, generate outputs, and finalize.\n./prompts/89-full-journey-e2e-test.md:12:- Assert that the final session has readable text, a docx asset, and an audio asset.\n./prompts/89-full-journey-e2e-test.md:23:- The test proves artifact generation and session resumability assumptions.\n./test-assets/README.md:7:- sample story briefs or structured workflow payloads\n./prompts/59-planning-funnel-e2e-test.md:7:Add an integration or end-to-end test that proves the workflow from genre selection through detailed outline works as one coherent funnel.\n./prompts/59-planning-funnel-e2e-test.md:11:- Assert that the session ends the flow with a usable structured outline and consistent stage state.\n./prompts/59-planning-funnel-e2e-test.md:23:- The test proves durable state evolves correctly across multiple stages.\n./prompts/36-conversation-memory-summaries.md:7:Create a compact memory mechanism so the system can retain story decisions and conversation context across long sessions without stuffing full chat history into every prompt.\n./prompts/36-conversation-memory-summaries.md:10:- Implement a rolling session summary that captures current story decisions, unresolved questions, and user preferences at key checkpoints.\n./prompts/36-conversation-memory-summaries.md:11:- Update the summary after meaningful events such as pitch selection, character selection, beat revisions, and composition interruptions.\n./prompts/36-conversation-memory-summaries.md:24:- A resumed session can restore context quickly.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:8:Storyteller is a session-based bedtime story studio, not a single-shot prompt demo. A user needs to move through a staged workflow, leave, come back later, and still see the current plan, generated text, generated audio, and recent activity.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:13:- session state needs to survive refreshes, restarts, and long-running work\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:14:- composition and audio generation are too slow and failure-prone to run inside request threads\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:24:All Gemini text, planning, composition, and narration calls belong behind backend-owned adapters and services.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:29:- The backend policy layer decides whether a model-suggested action is valid for the current workflow stage before state changes are accepted.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:33:PostgreSQL owns the structured state required to resume a story session.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:37:- session\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:38:- workflow stage\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:45:- composition jobs and segment progress\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:46:- audio jobs and segment progress\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:56:- Story exports, intermediate composition files, narration segments, and final audio artifacts live in object storage.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:63:The browser needs live updates during composition and audio generation, and those updates need to remain tied to durable backend state.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:65:- HTTP handles regular reads, writes, and workflow actions.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:66:- WebSockets handle session progress, job status, and incremental event delivery.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:67:- On reconnect, the client should rehydrate from durable session state and recent event history before continuing with live updates.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:69:The websocket channel is a delivery mechanism, not the source of truth. If a socket drops, the session must still be recoverable from PostgreSQL and storage.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:85:- They guide pitch generation, beat planning, and composition prompts.\n./docs/adr/0001-core-runtime-architecture.md:110:- Treat the durable event history as product data that can be queried during session resume.\n./prompts/24-design-tokens-and-accessibility-foundation.md:7:Establish visual and accessibility primitives early so the later workflow screens remain consistent and usable.\n./prompts/57-composition-prompt-assembly.md:32:`feat(prompt-57): composition prompt assembly`\n./prompts/04-docker-compose-foundation.summary.md:12:I preserved the pre-existing `browser` QA container because it is already part of the repo’s local verification workflow and still composes cleanly with the new stack.\n./prompts/04-docker-compose-foundation.summary.md:212:- I preserved the existing `browser` QA service even though the prompt only asked for four primary services. Removing it would have been a regression against the repo’s current development workflow.\n./prompts/84-reader-ui-with-navigation.md:18:- Convenient back-links to earlier stages\n./prompts/84-reader-ui-with-navigation.md:23:- The finalize stage does not trap the user.\n./prompts/99-release-checklist-and-future-roadmap.md:11:- Summarize the major open gaps or obvious future enhancements such as richer voice libraries, age presets, collaborative sessions, or visual storyboards.\n./prompts/29-frontend-websocket-client-skeleton.md:7:Lay the groundwork for live session updates on the frontend without fully wiring the backend transport yet.\n./prompts/29-frontend-websocket-client-skeleton.md:10:- Create a WebSocket client abstraction that can connect to a session-specific channel, reconnect, and dispatch typed events into the frontend state layer.\n./prompts/29-frontend-websocket-client-skeleton.md:11:- Add a thin reducer or event handler layer that can merge stage updates, chat events, and progress events into the current session state.\n./prompts/28-error-loading-and-feedback-states.md:7:Prepare the frontend to communicate progress and failure clearly before real asynchronous workflows arrive.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.codex.jsonlines:3:{\"type\":\"item.completed\",\"item\":{\"id\":\"item_0\",\"type\":\"agent_message\",\"text\":\"I’m inspecting the current repo state and the existing session/workflow code first so the domain model and state machine line up with what’s already implemented instead of introducing a parallel design.\"}}\n./prompts/58-usage-cost-and-latency-metrics.md:11:- Persist per-session summaries or lightweight counters for planning, composition, and audio usage.\n./prompts/58-usage-cost-and-latency-metrics.md:17:- Per-session usage summary\n./prompts/58-usage-cost-and-latency-metrics.md:23:- Model choices are visible per workflow stage.\n./prompts/32-ui-action-policy-engine.md:7:Create a deterministic policy layer that decides whether a proposed action is valid in the current session state and how it should be applied.\n./prompts/32-ui-action-policy-engine.md:10:- Implement validation rules based on current stage, selected entities, job status, and whether a change requires regeneration of downstream artifacts.\n./backend/app/worker/README.md:5:Future prompts should place composition, narration, and other long-running workflow workers here instead of embedding that logic in HTTP route handlers.\n./prompts/94-performance-pass.md:7:Keep the app responsive when a session accumulates lots of chat messages, revisions, segments, and artifacts.\n./prompts/94-performance-pass.md:10:- Profile or inspect the heaviest frontend and backend paths that will grow over long sessions.\n./prompts/94-performance-pass.md:11:- Optimize obvious hotspots such as large chat renders, session hydration payload size, and repeated expensive recomputations.\n./prompts/94-performance-pass.md:17:- Notes on long-session scaling decisions\n./prompts/94-performance-pass.md:22:- Longer sessions remain practical to open and use.\n./prompts/40-genre-selection-api-and-ui.md:7:Implement the first real workflow step: selecting a genre from the curated catalog.\n./prompts/40-genre-selection-api-and-ui.md:11:- Build the genre selection stage UI with selectable cards, helpful descriptions, and a clear next-step path.\n./prompts/40-genre-selection-api-and-ui.md:12:- Persist the selected genre durably and reflect the action in the session history and chat log.\n./prompts/40-genre-selection-api-and-ui.md:17:- Genre selection stage UI\n./prompts/40-genre-selection-api-and-ui.md:23:- The selected genre survives page refresh and session resume.\n./prompts/70-audio-settings-model-and-ui.md:7:Implement the audio stage where the user can choose narration voice, background music behavior, playback speed, and other audio preferences.\n./prompts/70-audio-settings-model-and-ui.md:11:- Build the audio settings stage UI with clear explanations of what each setting changes.\n./prompts/70-audio-settings-model-and-ui.md:12:- Persist these settings as durable session state and reflect them in chat/action history when changed.\n./prompts/70-audio-settings-model-and-ui.md:17:- Audio settings stage UI\n./prompts/70-audio-settings-model-and-ui.md:23:- Settings survive refresh and session resume.\n./prompts/69-composition-loop-e2e-test.md:10:- Simulate a composition job with mocked model outputs and verify that progress, chunk events, and final text land in durable state correctly.\n./prompts/69-composition-loop-e2e-test.md:11:- Test at least one interruption or rewrite path mid-composition.\n./prompts/69-composition-loop-e2e-test.md:12:- Assert that a resumed session shows the right latest story text and job state.\n./prompts/69-composition-loop-e2e-test.md:32:`feat(prompt-69): composition loop e2e test`\n./prompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md:7:Make session resume trustworthy by defining how the backend rebuilds the current workspace state from durable records.\n./prompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md:10:- Implement backend logic that can build a full session snapshot from relational records plus the latest accepted artifacts and summaries.\n./prompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md:11:- Decide when to use event replay, when to use materialized session state, and how to reconcile the two safely.\n./prompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md:12:- Expose a session hydration endpoint used by the workspace route on load.\n./prompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md:18:- Tests for resuming sessions in different stages\n./prompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md:22:- A user can leave mid-session and return to a coherent workspace.\n./prompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md:23:- Hydration works for completed sessions as well as in-progress ones.\n./prompts/38-session-replay-and-resume-hydration.md:32:`feat(prompt-38): session replay and resume hydration`\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md:7:Model the core business entities and the allowed stage transitions for a story creation session so the backend and frontend can agree on workflow rules.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md:10:- Define the major entities: story session, workflow stage, genre, tone profile, story brief, pitch, selected pitch, character sheet, beat sheet, story setup, composition segment, audio job, export asset, and event log entry.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md:11:- Describe the allowed stage order while still allowing safe backward edits and re-entry from past sessions.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md:18:- Shared enum or constants plan for workflow stages\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md:22:- The model supports resuming an unfinished session without guessing from UI state.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md:24:- The stage machine makes room for interruption and rewrite during composition.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md:28:Treat the session as the durable unit of work.\n./prompts/10-domain-model-and-state-machine.md:32:`feat(prompt-10): domain model and state machine`\n./prompts/08-repo-quality-tooling.summary.md:171:- The prompt asked for commands that can run in CI later, not for a CI workflow file in this task, so I stopped at deterministic local commands and docs.\n./prompts/22-workspace-two-pane-layout.md:7:Build the session workspace shell with a left chat pane taking roughly one-third of the screen and a main pane using the remaining space.\n./prompts/22-workspace-two-pane-layout.md:10:- Create the session workspace page with a responsive two-pane layout that honors the 1/3 chat and 2/3 main-pane requirement on desktop.\n./prompts/22-workspace-two-pane-layout.md:11:- Add a compact header showing session name, current stage, save status, and primary actions like return to home.\n./prompts/22-workspace-two-pane-layout.md:23:- The main pane has enough room for form workflows and live composition views.\n./prompts/09-initial-system-diagram-and-adr.yolopilot.jsonlines:8:{\"color\": \"cyan\", \"emoji\": \"\\ud83d\\udee0\\ufe0f\", \"event_type\": \"Command Finished\", \"message\": \"completed, exit 0: /bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' prompts/09-initial-system-diagram-and-adr.md\\\"\", \"raw_event\": {\"item\": {\"aggregated_output\": \"# 09 \\u2014 Initial System Diagram and First Architecture Decisions\\n\\nRead `base_prompt.md` first and preserve all prior prompt work.\\n\\n## Objective\\n\\nCapture the core architecture decisions early so later prompts can build on a stable mental model.\\n\\n## Build\\n- Write an ADR or equivalent note for the main architectural choices: backend-owned AI calls, Postgres-backed durable state, file-backed GCS emulator for assets, WebSocket-based live updates, and a separate worker process for long-running jobs.\\n- Add one lightweight system diagram in Markdown or Mermaid showing browser, API, worker, database, object storage, and Gemini integrations.\\n- Record the decision that word count, runtime, and chapter count are soft planning hints rather than hard constraints.\\n\\n## Deliverables\\n\\n- `docs/adr/` or similar notes\\n- A simple system diagram\\n- A written statement of the product\\u2019s soft-constraint philosophy\\n\\n## Acceptance checks\\n\\n- Later contributors can tell where real-time updates and long-running tasks belong.\\n- The diagram includes session resume and durable event history as first-class concepts.\\n- The architecture notes reflect the actual product brief instead of a generic app template.\\n\\n## Notes\\n\\nUse plain language. This doc is for builders, not for impressing anyone.\\n\\n## Suggested commit label\\n\\n`feat(prompt-09): initial system diagram and adr`\\n\", \"command\": \"/bin/zsh -lc \\\"sed -n '1,240p' prompts/09-initial-system-diagram-and-adr.md\\\"\", \"exit_code\": 0, \"id\": \"item_1\", \"status\": \"completed\", \"type\": \"command_execution\"}, \"type\": \"item.completed\"}, \"task_display_context\": {\"event_number\": 8, \"prompt_index\": 10, \"prompt_name\": \"09 \\u2014 Initial System Diagram and First Architecture Decisions\", \"prompt_total\": 100}, \"timestap\": \"2026-03-31T22:15:13-07:00\"}\n./prompts/09-initial-system-diagram-and-adr.yolopilot.jsonlines:12:{\"color\": \"cyan\", \"emoji\": \"\\ud83d\\udee0\\ufe0f\", \"event_typ